The film released in Japanese theaters on August 2, 1986. It performed below expectations at the box office, but later achieved commercial success through rereleases, earning over&nbsp;US$157 million&nbsp;as of 2021. An English dub commissioned by&nbsp;[Tokuma Shoten](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tokuma_Shoten)&nbsp;in 1988 was distributed in North America by&nbsp;[Streamline Pictures](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Streamline_Pictures), and another dub was produced by&nbsp;[Disney](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walt_Disney_Pictures)&nbsp;in 1998, released internationally by&nbsp;[Buena Vista](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walt_Disney_Studios_Home_Entertainment)&nbsp;in 2003. The film's score was composed by&nbsp;[Joe Hisaishi](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Hisaishi), who would become a close collaborator of Miyazaki's; Hisaishi also composed a reworked soundtrack for the 2003 English dub. The film was generally acclaimed by critics, though the 2003 English dub received mixed reviews. It was well-received by audiences, being voted as one of the greatest animated films of all time in later years. The film also received several notable accolades.&nbsp;*Castle in the Sky*&nbsp;has since earned "[cult status](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cult_film)",[
